Inter and Intra Regional Analysis of NO2 Levels

Author

Sheeba Moghal, Tiana Le, Pranav Patil, Dheeraj Oruganty

Introduction

Air pollution is a public health and environmental issue (Pope and Dockery, 2006). The health effects of poor air quality can cause serious health problems, such as increased morbidity and mortality in the respiratory, cardiovascular and cerebrovascular systems (WHO, 2013). The impact of air pollution also differs by socioeconomic status for individuals and in developing countries, hence considering it to be another factor towards the contribution of global health inequality. In addition to impact on health, air pollution leads to greater economic costs, such as impact on agricultural crops and damage to buildings and infrastructure (WHO, 2021). WHO (2021) states that air pollution-related climate changes are also associated with higher costs and environmental degradation. They also state that air pollution results in the loss of trillions of dollars, loss of healthy life, and cause millions of deaths annually.

As it has been associated with asthma, lung cancer, and lower life expectancy (Wang, 2016), an essential tool for informing the public about air quality is the Air Quality Index (AQI), that summarizes the concentrations of different pollutants such as particulate matter, ozone, sulfur dioxide, carbon monoxide, and nitrogen dioxide (NO2). Its importance resides in the fact that it offers a clear, easily understandable metric that helps people, groups, and authorities recognise and manage the possible health risks linked to air pollution.

Nitrogen dioxide (NO2) linked to industrial processes and vehicle combustion is a particularly notable indicator among the pollutants monitored by the Air Quality Index (AQI). Despite efforts to improve air quality, many countries are still impacted by the effects of air pollution (Li, 2016). The respiratory irritant NO2 is a major factor in determining the general quality of the air. Hence, it is crucial to comprehend NO2 levels in various regions for a number of reasons. In the first place, it makes it possible to pinpoint locations with high pollution levels and implement focused interventions to enhance air quality. It also functions as a tool for assessing the efficacy of programmes and policies aimed at controlling pollution. Furthermore, the comparative study of NO2 levels aids in the development of strategies to lower emissions and improve air quality by offering insights into the various sources of pollution.

Hence, the aim of this data science project is to analyze the effects of NO2, a measure of air quality, in different regions, countries, and between different years within countries. The analysis begins with comparing the WHO classified regions, the European Region and the South East Asia Region. A country was also analyzed within each region. These countries are France and India. In these countries, the difference in NO2 was analyzed between two different years within the same country. Finally, to understand if global NO2 has been changing with time, NO2 emissions were classified and tested for independence between years.

Literature Review

People are exposed to multiple different types of air pollutants. The World Health Organization (WHO) acknowledges that more research is required to improve models by including these multiple pollutants (WHO, 2021). However, as recognized by the WHO, most evidence on air quality and health still focuses on how single markers, like NO2, impact air pollution on the risk of adverse health outcomes. Since 2005, the WHO has been publishing air quality guidelines leading to new studies and increased awareness of air quality issues. This has led to advances in measuring levels of pollutants internationally. However, despite these advances, coverage of monitoring pollutants is still inadequate and often limited to major cities. There is inadequate monitoring in rural areas and areas outside of major cities in many countries. The dataset collected from the WHO Air Quality database reflects these issues. After reviewing the data, NO2 had the most coverage internationally.

Excessive NO2 is also dangerous for the environment. According to the US EPA (1993, 1995), NO2 â(a) absorbs visible solar radiation and contributes to impaired atmospheric visibility; (b) it absorbs visible radiation and has a potentially direct role in global climate change.â Reducing NO2 is important in mitigating climate change caused by air pollutants. The WHO publishes guidelines for mitigating NO2. Recommending interim targets, the WHO (2021) recommends a first interim target of 40 Î¼g/m3 eventually reducing to 10 Î¼g/m3 annually. According to Jarvis et. al.Â (2010), the annual average nitrogen dioxide indoor under the guideline of 40 Î¼g/m3 is consistent and recommended by existing WHO air quality guideline.

The European Region and the South East Asia Region have distinctive differences in NO2 emissions. According to Jion et al.Â (2023), there is a rise in the NO2 and SO2 pollution levels in Asian countries (like Bangladesh, China, Pakistan, Nepal, Malaysia, Iran, Kuwait, India, and Japan), largely due to industrialization, urbanization, and economic development. Analyzing Asia and Europe on a comparative scale showcases their distinctive industrial profiles. Asia is rapidly industrializing, driven by robust economic growth, globalization, and increasing population. However, it is important to recognize that developed countries may also indirectly contribute to the industrialization in developing countries by outsourcing the production of consumer goods outside their borders (Kolcava et al., 2019). According to Kolcava et al., along with outsourcing consumer goods, developed countries also outsource environmental burdens like air pollution.

Data and Methodology

Data

During the compilation of the data, the information is provided by the World Health Organizationâs (WHO)âs AQI report for the year of 2022 which serves to be the best source (WHO, n.d). The WHOâs data is derived from a range of sources, including official country reports submitted upon request, national and subnational reports, and relevant websites. These sources primarily furnished the measurements of Particulate Matter 10 (PM10) and Particulate Matter 2.5 (PM 2.5.)

This dataset is enriched with findings from the Global Burden of Disease project, integrating ground measurements with other pertinent environmental data. For specific pollutants like NO2, the WHO incorporated research, including studies by Larkin et al.Â (2017). Additional contributions came from regional networks like Clean Air for Asia, the European Environment Agencyâs air quality e-reporting database, and the AirNow Programme of U.S. embassies and consulates. In cases lacking official data, the WHO turned to peer-reviewed journals to fill in the gaps.

The dataset focuses on annual mean concentrations of PM10, PM2.5, and NO2, offering city or town-wide averages rather than data from individual monitoring stations. In analyzing urban air pollution levels, the WHO employed a rigorous approach. Mean values reported by cities were used directly, while averages were calculated from eligible monitoring stations when explicit mean values were absent. Itâs noteworthy that these stations might not entirely represent a cityâs overall background pollution, as they could be located in areas with higher pollution levels. The WHO excluded data from such hotspots to ensure a more representative analysis.

Another critical aspect considered by the WHO was the temporal coverage of the data, i.e., the number of days per year with available measurements. For cities with multiple monitoring stations, an average of their temporal coverage is calculated to represent the cityâs overall average. While not always available, many reporting agencies set minimum thresholds for the number of days a station must operate to include its data in the cityâs average pollution level assessment.

Additionally, to enhance this comprehensive dataset, population data is collected from the World Bank (World Bank, 2022). This data is integrated to explore the relationship between population dynamics and air quality measurements. This integration aimed to provide a deeper understanding of how demographic factors might influence or correlate with changes in air pollution levels over time.

Data Exploration And Pre-Processing

The real-world data is never clean, often consisting of missing values, improperly imputed numbers, etc., that needs to be cleaned thoroughly for better data analysis purposes. The dataset collected from WHO is no different and has a lot of missing coverage from a lot of cities, this is expected as coverage across cities differ on how to report data and sometimes, not meeting the best standards. Hence, the columns of references, number and type of monitoring stations and status are dropped since they do not contribute to the data science question.

Additionally, for the estimation of population figures during the analysis, there is reliance on comprehensive data obtained from the World Bank. This data can be accessed publicly at (World Bank Population Data, 2022). It encompasses global population statistics, which are meticulously compiled and regularly updated by the World Bank. This dataset served as a crucial component in our demographic analysis, providing reliable and up-to-date population figures for various geographical regions and countries under study.

For the purposes of pre-processing, data analysis and statistial testing which will be discussed in the later parts of this project, R has been used. For Exploratory Analysis, Python has been used.

In terms of the NO2 temporal coverage, the data was subsetted for the values greater than 90% for easier air quality monitering and hotspots identification purposes, enabling more coverage.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is essential for understanding changes in NO2 concentration over time in various nations and areas. This facilitates the identification of patterns, trends, and possible outliers in the data through statistical tools and visualisations. For this project, EDA has acted as a usual tool for global NO2 concentration analysis as it gives a preliminary understanding of temporal trends and geographical disparities, thus making it easier to interpret data, leading to more focused hypothesis formulations. For this EDA, the Pythonâs plotly library has been used since it is more interactive, showcasing the output of the plots better and has better view, which is much better than R.

Code

The above graph shows the relationship between four variables: population, NO2 temporal coverage (%), NO2 (Âµg/m3), and average NO2. The pairplot shows that there is a positive correlation between population and NO2 (Âµg/m3). This means that as population increases, NO2 (Âµg/m3) also tends to increase. This is likely because areas with higher populations tend to have more industrial activity and traffic, which are both sources of NO2. The pairplot also shows that there is a positive correlation between NO2 temporal coverage (%) and NO2 (Âµg/m3). This means that as the percentage of time that NO2 is measured increases, the average NO2 concentration also tends to increase. This is likely because areas with better NO2 monitoring tend to be more urbanized and have higher levels of air pollution. The pairplot does not show a clear correlation between population and NO2 temporal coverage (%) or between average NO2 (Âµg/m3) and NO2 temporal coverage (%) This suggests that there is no simple relationship between these variables.

Methodology

T test

When two independent groups have different variances and unequal sample sizes, a statistical test called the Welch t-test, also called the Welchâs unequal variances t-test, is used to compare the means of the two groups. It is a development of the conventional Studentâs t-test, which counts on the two groupsâ variances being equal.

Usually the hypothesis is formulated for this, where

\(H_0\)= The means of the output are equal

\(H_1\)= The means of the output are not equal (You can specify âgreaterâ than or âlessâ than too)

The test statistic for the Welch t-test is calculated as:

\[ t = \frac{\bar{X}_1 - \bar{X}_2}{\sqrt{\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \frac{s_2^2}{n_2}}} \]

where \((\bar{X}_1, \bar{X}_2)\) are the sample means, \((s_1^2, s_2^2)\) are the sample variances, and \((n_1, n_2)\) are the sample sizes of the two groups.

The degrees of freedom for the Welch t-test are calculated using the Welch-Satterthwaite equation: \[ \text{df} \approx \frac{\left(\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \frac{s_2^2}{n_2}\right)^2}{\frac{\left(\frac{s_1^2}{n_1}\right)^2}{n_1 - 1} + \frac{\left(\frac{s_2^2}{n_2}\right)^2}{n_2 - 1}} \]

The test statistic calculated is then calculated on basis of which one either rejects or accepts the null hypothesis.

The Welch t-test makes the assumption that data is measured on an interval or ratio scale, and that the populations from which samples are taken have a roughly normal distribution. It is also assumed that random sampling, independence of observations, and homogeneity of variances within groups exist. Although the test is resistant to deviations from normalcy and unequal variances, the outcomes could be affected by extreme deviations. When comparing the means of independent groups with unequal variances, it works well. When variances between groups are not equal, the Welch t-test performs better than the Studentâs t-test. Without assuming equal variances, it yields accurate results, especially in small sample sizes. Because of this, it is a strong option for comparing means in situations where the Studentâs t-test may not be as trustworthy. (Duke University, n.d.; Zach, 2019; Glen, n.d.)

Chi Square Test

The chi-square test of independence evaluates if two categorical variables significantly correlate with one another. In a contingency table, the observed and expected frequencies are compared as part of the test. As part of the test, a contingency table showing the observed frequencies of the variablesâ joint occurrences must be created. On the presumption that the variables are independent, expected frequencies are computed. Next, the chi-square statistic is calculated to determine how much the observed and expected frequencies differ from one another. A greater departure from independence is indicated by a higher chi-square value.

To calculate the chi-square test of independance, you set up the null and the alternative hypothesis first where

\(H_0\) : There is absence of significant association between the two variables

\(H_1\) : There is presence of significant association between the two variables

The contingency table looks like this:

\[ \begin{array}{cccccc} & \text{Category 1} & \text{Category 2} & \ldots & \text{Category j} & \text{Total} \\ \text{Group A} & O_{11} & O_{12} & \ldots & O_{1j} & R_1 \\ \text{Group B} & O_{21} & O_{22} & \ldots & O_{2j} & R_2 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots \\ \text{Group i} & O_{i1} & O_{i2} & \ldots & O_{ij} & R_i \\ \text{Total} & C_1 & C_2 & \ldots & C_j & N \\ \end{array} \]

The expected frequencies are calculated using;

\[ E_{ij} = \frac{\text{Sum of row } i \times \text{Sum of column } j}{\text{Grand total}} \]

The chi-square is calculated using:

\[ \chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{r} \sum_{j=1}^{c} \frac{(O_{ij} - E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}} \]

where \(r\) is the number of rows and \(c\) is the number of columns

The degrees of freedom is calculated using:

\[ df = (r-1) \cdot (c-1) \]

The null hypothesis is rejected or accepted if the calculated chi-square statistic is less than 0.05 after comparing it to the critical value from the chi-square distribution table with df degrees of freedom.

The chi-square test of independence relies on the assumptions of mutually exclusive categories, random sampling, and categorical data. For results that can be trusted, a sufficient sample size is needed. To ensure the validity of the test results, the test also assumes the independence of observations and that the expected frequency in each cell is not too low. (Statistics Solutions, n.d.; Penn State World Campus, n.d.; University of Utah, n.d.)

Bootstrapping

A statistical technique called bootstrapping generates numerous simulated samples by resampling a single dataset. With a variety of sample statistics, this procedure enables one to compute standard errors, creating confidence intervals, and carrying out the hypothesis testing. Known for being more widely applicable and easier to comprehend than traditional hypothesis testing techniques, bootstrap methods are an alternative. This approach is especially useful when sample sizes are constrained or when it is difficult to determine the underlying statistical properties analytically.

In order to bootstrap a distribution, multiple datasets of the same size as the original sample are created, a selected statistic of interest is determined for each dataset, and a distribution is then built using the resampled statistics. By acting as a stand-in for the statisticâs sampling variability, this distribution makes it easier to estimate confidence intervals and conduct hypothesis testing. Next, bias can be computed from both the boostrapped sample and the original sample to determine which one performs better, based on the user-defined question.

Compared to parametric methods, boostrapping has the advantage of requiring fewer distributional assumptions; however, it still relies on the assumption that the observed data accurately represents the underlying population distribution. Additionally, it relies on the randomness of the sampling process and the independence of observations among samples to produce accurate and impartial results. (Hickman, 2023; University of Washington, n.d.)

Statistical Testing

Test 1: Did South East Asia Region have more NO2 (Âµg/m3) emissions than the European Region in 2019?

To compare the average NO2 (Âµg/m3) in the South East Asia Region compared to the European Region, a Welch Two Sample t-test is performed. In preparation for t-test, the assumptions of the test are assessed before comparing the appropriate variables. First, each observation is assumed to be independent of each observation in the sample. Each region included NO2 (Âµg/m3) observations for each city in each respective region in the year 2019. Second, each city is assumed to be randomly sampled in the dataset. Third, in this subset, the number of observations for each region had the best balance compared to other years and other regions. The South East Asia Region and European Region has the greatest number of samples in 2019. Finally, the data is reviewed for normality (Statology, 2021).

Test 2.1: Does France have less NO2 (Âµg/m3) emissions in 2016 than in 2010?

Given that South East Asian has greater NO2 (Âµg/m3) emissions than Europe, additional testing was performed on France that belongs to the European Region and India from the South East Asian Region

To test this hypothesis, two-sample bootstrap test for the ratio of means of NO2 (Âµg/m3) is performed. Bootstrap testing is a powerful tool for this dataset. Although the original data has over 32,190 observations, the dataset decreased to 16,364 after excluding columns with majority missing data and low temporal coverage. When choosing the variables to analyze, the variables with the most complete data are selected. In France, this resulted in about 286 observations in 2018 and 304 observations in 2010, which are closer to each other in terms of frequency counts. Hence, the two-sample bootstrap test can be performed on this constrained sample size between the years 2010 and 2016.

The boostrapping for this is performed with a sample size of 100,000 using the ratio of means. After the calculation of the bias of 0.03 which is almost non-existant, the boostrap test shows the 95% confidence in the alternative hypothesis.

Code 
df_france <- df[df$WHO.Country.Name=="France", ]
df_france_2010 <- df_france[df_france$Measurement.Year == "2010", ]
df_france_2016 <- df_france[df_france$Measurement.Year == "2016", ]
N <- 100000

ratiomeans<- numeric(N)

for (i in 1:N)
{
  fr_sample_2010 <- sample(df_france_2010$NO2[df_france_2010$Measurement.Year == '2010'], length(df_france_2010), replace = TRUE)
  fr_sample_2016 <- sample(df_france_2016$NO2[df_france_2016$Measurement.Year == '2016'], length(df_france_2016), replace = TRUE)
  ratiomeans[i] <- mean(fr_sample_2010)/mean(fr_sample_2016)
}

quantile(ratiomeans, c(0.025, 0.975))

fr_mean_2010 <- mean(df_france_2010$NO2[df_france_2010$Measurement.Year == '2010'])
fr_mean_2016 <- mean(df_france_2016$NO2[df_france_2016$Measurement.Year == '2016'])
ratio_actual <- fr_mean_2010/fr_mean_2016
bias= round(mean(ratiomeans)-mean(ratio_actual), digits = 3) #estimated bias

print(paste("The estimated bias is", bias))

0.783456920811503

1.83791169131899

Conclusion: Yes, France has decreased their NO2 (Âµg/m3) emissions in 2016.

Test 3: Was global NO2 dependent on Year?

To compare if global NO2 emissions are independent of year, a Chi-square test is performed. In this subset, all countries and cities are included from the cleaned dataset. According to Jarvis et al.Â (2010), âthe annual average indoor nitrogen dioxide guideline of 40 (Âµg/m3), consistent with the existing WHO air quality guideline, is recommended.â The data included in our analysis ranged from 2010 to 2019. Since this guideline is published in the date range of the collected data, NO2 (Âµg/m3) values that fell at and below 40 (Âµg/m3) annually are categorized in a new column as within the WHO guidelines. NO2 values that are greater than 40 Î¼g/m3 are categorized as above.

The new WHO guideline column and the year column meets the required assumption that both variables in the Chi-square test are categorical. Like in t-test, each observation is assumed to be independent. A contingency table is calculated with the number of cities meeting within or above the WHO guidelines for each year. The values in the contingency table are mutually exclusive.

According to the existing WHO air quality guidelines, a new column is added labeling NO2 above and within 40 (Âµg/m3) (Jarvis et al., 2010) to the merged dataset.

Code 
df$WHO.Guideline <- ifelse(df$NO2 >= 41.0, "above", "within")

Results and Discussion

After performing the Welch Two Sample t-test on average NO2 (Âµg/m3), the p-value was is less than 0.05. This result supports the alternative hypothesis that NO2 (Âµg/m3) emissions were greater in the South East Asia Region than in the European Region. This is consistent with previous research that has found a rise in NO2 (Âµg/m3) in the Asian Region (Jion et al., 2023).

Two-sample bootstrap test for ratio of means of NO2 (Âµg/m3) performed to assess if France NO2 (Âµg/m3) has less emissions in 2016 compared to 2010. The t-test resulted in a p-value much less than 0.05. After bootstrapping the ratio of means, the confidence interval is approximately (0.784, 1.835). Since the confidence interval includes values greater than 0, the alternative hypothesis is supported. Therefore, France has less NO2 (Âµg/m3) in 2016 compared to 2010.

To analyze a country within the South East Asia Region, another t-test is performed to see if India had greater emissions in 2014 than in 2014. The results show a p-value greater than 0.05, which fails to reject the null hypothesis. India had greater NO2 (Âµg/m3) emissions in 2018 compared to 2014.

To determine if NO2 (Âµg/m3) is dependent on year, Chi-square test is performed. The p-value was much less than 0.05. This result supports the alternative hypothesis. The compliance with recommended NO2 (Âµg/m3) is dependent on the year. The compliance with recommended NO2 (Âµg/m3) differs between the years.

Conclusion

Our study analyzed the levels of NO2 (Âµg/m3), which is a key indicator of air quality. Using existing data from the WHO Air Quality Database, the data was transformed from a real-world messy format into actionable conclusions and evidence to inform better decision making. The dataset was challenging to analyze because the measurement of NO2 (Âµg/m3) was not consistent between the many stations that monitor NO2. However, using the data available, we were still able to find notable differences in NO2 (Âµg/m3). The analysis found that NO2 (Âµg/m3) was greater in the South East Asia Region than in the European Region in 2019, emphasizing the importance of regional disparities in air pollution. However, when examining NO2 (Âµg/m3) emission in India from 2018 to 2014, we did not observe a change. The differences underscore the importance of policy and government to monitor NO2. Better collection and coverage of measured NO2 in future years can improve the results of the statistical analysis.

Furthermore, our study also explored NO2 (Âµg/m3) levels in France, showcasing a meaningful reduction in emissions from 2010 to 2016. This finding underscores the potential positive impact of target measures in migrating air pollution as recommended by the WHO.

From our findings, France showed a reduction in emissions while India showed an increase in emissions. According to Jion et al.Â (2023), countries in Asia like India may have more air pollution due to industrialization, urbanization, and economic development. On the other hand, it is important to consider how globalization and international trade may play a role in how developed countries outsource the industrial burden to Asia (Kolcava 2019). Although the data shows which country is performing better, it is important to understand the history and the context of this trend.

The analysis also revealed that global NO2 compliance trends vary between years. This emphasized that adherence to recommended NO2 levels depended on years. More research can be done to better understand if NO2 is increasing or decreasing over the years. This research will require statistical methods taught outside the DSAN 5100 course in Probabilistic Modeling and Statistical Computing. However, given the statistical methods and data currently available, these meaningful findings open the doors for new data science questions. These findings reveal the beginning of potential findings that can come from real-world data.

Overall, our research contributes valuable insights into the complexities of air quality dynamics, advocating for ongoing efforts to monitor and address air pollution on both regional and global scales. These findings hold implications for public health and environmental policies, urging a continued focus on sustainable practices to improve air quality for the well-being of communities worldwide.
